      "question": "If $\\sin(A + B) = 1$ and $\\cos(A - B) = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$, where $0^\\circ < A + B \\leq 90^\\circ$ and $A > B$, find the values of $A$ and $B$.",
      "answer": "A = 60^\\circ, B = 30^\\circ",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Use the given trigonometric values to equate the angles.",
          "Set up a system of linear equations in terms of A and B.",
          "Solve the system using the elimination method."
        ],
        "derivation": "\\sin(A+B) = 1 = \\sin 90^\\circ \\implies A+B = 90^\\circ \\quad (1) \\\\ \\cos(A-B) = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} = \\cos 30^\\circ \\implies A-B = 30^\\circ \\quad (2) \\\\ \\text{Adding (1) and (2): } 2A = 120^\\circ \\implies A = 60^\\circ \\\\ \\text{Substituting A in (1): } 60^\\circ + B = 90^\\circ \\implies B = 30^\\circ"
      },
